ce:section.ce:para:
ML models can achieve a high classification accuracy after being trained on an appropriate dataset, including quantitative and qualitative representations of all possible conditions [17,29]. In addition, the dataset needs to be a collection of data that ensure the robustness and adaptability of the system to new environments, regardless of illumination conditions and camera optics. Therefore, in this study, images were captured using smartphones (iPhone 6, iPhone 11, LG 6, and Samsung Galaxy A23) from Android and iOS operating systems with different camera properties (Table 1
                        ) under the combination of LED (L), Fluorescent (F), and Sunlight (S) to ensure inter-phone repeatability and robustness. Besides, imaging was repeated for three angles (60°, 90°, and 120°) to consider rotation and direction effects. The L (Osram 9 W), F (Klite 6 W), and S (Philips 5.5 W) light sources were selected to ensure imaging under different light characteristics, including warm (2700 K), neutral (4000 K), and cold (6500 K) colors, respectively. The distances between light sources and smartphones were set as 20, 24 and 28 cm for L, F and S, respectively. Moreover, the images were captured at an incidence angle of 30° relative to the distance of 10 cm from the smartphone to the film. The film response (Table 2
                        ) was captured with nine different ammonia gas concentration values for seven illuminations (L, F, S, LF, LS, FS, LFS) in auto mode using four smartphones and three angles, resulting in 756 images for the dataset. In this respect, Henry's law was used to calculate gaseous ammonia concentration based on the partial vapor pressure of ammonia at 23 °C and its starting concentration by changing the relative concentrations of 1 M of ammonium chloride and 0.2 M of sodium hydroxide in 20 mL solution [30]. To achieve in situ ammonia gas concentrations equivalent to 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 90, and 120 mg N/100 g, a specified amount of stock solutions was introduced to each beaker of 25 mL. Next, the film (2 cm × 2 cm) was attached to the cellophane, and the inner surface of the cellophane with the film was exposed to ammonia solutions at 23 °C. The images of the films were taken after 24 h exposure. Before training the ML classifiers, the dataset was pre-processed in the computer, as discussed in the next.
